{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c9e7ad3b-4216-4ff2-82ec-2413a02d8920","content":"Since you're using **Microsoft.Testing.Platform** (via `global.json`), you can enable hang detection directly from the command line:\n\n```\ndotnet test -- --hang-dump --hang-dump-timeout 5m\n```\n\nThe `--hang-dump` flag enables hang detection, and `--hang-dump-timeout 5m` sets the threshold to 5 minutes. When a test hangs, it will be terminated and a dump will be produced to help you diagnose the root cause.\n\nWant me to run the tests with this configuration now?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"636309b1-0cbc-4a93-ad82-3528ec95aca3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"This is a .NET project using MSTest 3.8.0 with Microsoft.Testing.Platform runner. To add a 5-minute hang timeout, I need to configure the test platform's hang detection.\n\nFor Microsoft.Testing.Platform, you can pass `--hang-dump-timeout` or configure it via a `.runsettings` file. Since they're using MSTest with Microsoft.Testing.Platform runner, the hang detection can be enabled via command line arguments:\n\n```\ndotnet test --hang-dump-timeout 5m\n```\n\nOr via a `.runsettings` file with the `RunConfiguration` section.\n\nActually, with Microsoft.Testing.Platform, the hang dump feature is available through the `--hang-dump` option. \n\nThe most straightforward approach is to use the command line with both the hang dump flag and timeout parameter, or configure it in a runsettings file. I'll provide the user with the direct command they can run.","outputTokens":434},"id":"273b0dd7-ebde-43e3-a973-09ab359b9bb8","timestamp":"2026-04-03T01:49:54.162Z","parentId":"ae61894a-75bc-4dc8-b41f-e36e644aa444"}
